  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Mount Cotton sits roughly 25 kilometres south-east of the Brisbane CBD, on the rural-residential edge of the Redlands hinterland between Capalaba and Redland Bay. It is a true acreage market, with most properties on lots well above a hectare, and the buyer profile reflects that: lifestyle buyers, hobby-farm purchasers, families wanting privacy and space, and a steady stream of inner-Brisbane and interstate buyers who have decided that the next stage of life is going to look very different from the inner suburbs. Selling in Mount Cotton in 2026 means understanding that this is a specialist market with its own rules, not a standard residential campaign that happens to be on a bigger block.</p>

      <p>The defining feature of the Mount Cotton buyer is patience combined with conviction. They have usually been searching the acreage corridor from Burbank through to Mount Cotton, Sheldon and Redland Bay for months, sometimes years. They know what useable acreage looks like. They know what good water security, fencing and shedding should cost to replicate. When they see a property that genuinely meets their list, they move with confidence, but the price they will pay is anchored in the practical infrastructure rather than emotional inner-suburban factors. Pricing accuracy here means understanding what the buyer is actually paying for.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Mount Cotton</h2>
      <p>Lifestyle families are the dominant buyer segment. These are typically established families, often with school-aged children and a parent who works from home or is in flexible employment, who have decided that space, privacy and a semi-rural setting are worth the longer commute. They have usually been renting or owning closer to Brisbane, have done the maths on the commute and the lifestyle trade-off, and arrive in Mount Cotton with a clear list: useable acreage, a quality main dwelling, shedding, ideally town-water connection where available, and reliable road access.</p>

      <p>Hobby-farm and small-scale equine buyers form a consistent second segment. These buyers are highly specific about what they need: cleared and fenced paddocks, water security through dams or tanks, stockyards or stables, and access for floats and trucks. They will pay a clear premium for properties that have these features already in place rather than requiring significant capital works.</p>

      <p>Inner-Brisbane downsizers buying a "tree change" form a smaller but meaningful third segment. These are often empty-nesters who have sold inner-city properties at premium prices and are exchanging that capital for space, privacy and a manageable acreage with a quality dwelling. They are generally less interested in working infrastructure (paddocks, stockyards) and more interested in the dwelling, the outlook and the privacy.</p>

      <p>Interstate buyers, particularly from Sydney and Melbourne, are a regular presence in Mount Cotton. They typically inspect over a single weekend, are price-sensitive but conviction-driven once a property meets their criteria, and rely heavily on the campaign materials and virtual tours during their decision process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Mount Cotton</h2>
      <p>Land usability is the single largest value driver. Total acreage matters, but the proportion of the block that is genuinely useable, cleared, level enough to graze or build on and accessible by vehicle, matters more. A five-acre block where four acres are useable will consistently outperform a ten-acre block where seven acres are steep, bushland-locked or impractical to access.</p>

      <p>Water and shedding infrastructure are the next major drivers. Town water connection, where available in Mount Cotton, adds material value because it removes the buyer's concern about tank capacity and dam reliability in dry periods. Substantial sheds (machinery shed, workshop, hay storage) are valued highly by working acreage buyers. Fencing, stockyards, dam capacity and bore access all factor into the buyer's mental price model.</p>

      <p>The dwelling itself matters, but in a different way to standard residential markets. A premium dwelling on a poor block will rarely outperform a solid dwelling on an excellent block. Buyers in this segment have a clear sense that they can renovate or extend the house over time, but the land and infrastructure are largely fixed at the time of purchase. Road access (sealed road versus gravel, frontage length, ease of float and truck access) also drives buyer response materially.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your Mount Cotton property for sale</h2>
      <p>Preparation for an acreage campaign is fundamentally different from a residential campaign. The land has to be presented as cleanly and honestly as the house. Slash long grass, address fence damage, tidy stockyards and shedding, remove disused vehicles and rubbish, and present dams and water infrastructure clearly. Photography that shows the land in context, ideally with drone footage demonstrating boundaries, useable areas, water assets and access, is essential. Acreage buyers will not commit without understanding the land properly.</p>

      <p>The dwelling deserves standard presentation work: thorough clean, fresh paint where needed, addressed minor defects and tidy outdoor entertaining spaces. Acreage buyers are practical and will not be pushed by premium fit-outs, but they are deterred by deferred maintenance or evidence that the property has not been cared for.</p>

      <p>A pre-sale building and pest inspection is genuinely valuable in Mount Cotton, where dwelling age varies widely and where many homes have been extended or modified over decades. A water assessment for tank capacity, dam reliability and bore output is also worth considering, particularly for properties without town-water connection. The more clearly the seller can describe the working infrastructure of the property, the more confidently the acreage buyer will move.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Mount Cotton</h2>
      <p>The Mount Cotton seasonal pattern is less pronounced than in standard residential markets, but it is real. Autumn (late February through May) is generally the strongest window: the land is at its best after summer growth, fencing and paddocks present well, and the lifestyle buyer is active and motivated before the next school year and the cooler winter inspection conditions. Spring also performs well for the same reasons, and listings can move quickly when interstate buyers travel for spring weekends.</p>

      <p>Winter and mid-summer are typically slower windows. Winter dryness can make the land present less favourably, particularly for properties without irrigation or strong water security, and interstate buyer travel slows. A campaign that launches in the strongest seasonal windows tends to capture concentrated buyer attention, which matters in a market where the buyer pool is smaller and more focused than a residential equivalent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Mount Cotton</h2>
      <p>Mount Cotton acreage typically sells in 35 to 75 days, longer than the standard Brisbane residential market because the buyer pool is more specialised and the decision process more considered. Well-presented properties with strong useable acreage, quality infrastructure and accurate pricing often conclude in the lower part of that range, sometimes faster when the right interstate or inner-Brisbane buyer arrives early in the campaign. Properties requiring significant works, those with limited useable land relative to total area, or those priced above what the comparable acreage sales support, can take materially longer. Pricing the property in line with what the working buyer actually values, rather than in line with online estimators that frequently misread acreage, is the most important factor under the seller's control.</p>

